blogPosts.title: Tempo Merkin
blogPosts.description: Regular Merkin, in cadence, with a 3-count down and a 1-count up.

blogPosts.title: Surfer Merkin
blogPosts.description: Perform a 360-degree jump, then go down for a merkin, pop back up, and repeat.

blogPosts.title: Star Jack Burpee
blogPosts.description: A burpee variation that includes a StarJack instead of the jump at the end. The StarJack is performed by jumping and raising your arms and legs out to your sides, so your body forms an 'X' in mid-air.

blogPosts.title: Smurf Jacks
blogPosts.description: Side straddle hop performed in the squat position. Can be done in cadence or OYO.

blogPosts.title: Sixty Second Arm Circles aka SSACs
blogPosts.description: Sixty Second Arm Circles aka SSACs
blogPosts.imageAltText: Sixty Second Arm Circles aka SSACs

blogPosts.title: Scorpion Dry Dock
blogPosts.description: A variation of the Carolina Dry Dock where one leg is hoisted in the air, higher than your six. Perform a specified number of reps, then switch legs.

blogPosts.title: Sally's Cousin
blogPosts.description: Variation of 'Bring Sally Up' - Play 'Flower' by Moby. Instead of starting in the merkin position, begin in a downward squat position and hold. Each time 'Bring Sally Up' is sung, stand up; when 'Bring Sally Down' is sung, return to the squat position. Youll definitely feel the burn in your quads!

blogPosts.title: Bulgarian Split Squat
blogPosts.description: Use a bench or a partner's back while they hold a plank position. Extend one leg out roughly 24 inches, with the other leg placed on the bench or your partners back. Squat down until your knee is nearly touching the ground, then return to the starting position. Perform the movement on the down command, typically in sets of 15-20 reps per leg. To modify, add weight using a coupon, ruck, or sandbag.

blogPosts.title: Gargoyle
blogPosts.description: A variation of the Monkey Humper, which is a half-squat performed while grabbing the inside of your ankles. In this variation, the exercise is performed on a coupon, bench, or any elevated surface.

blogPosts.title: Lunge Worm
blogPosts.description: Lunge Walk with each leg, then do an inch worm with two Merkins at the bottom before inching back up. When returning to standing position from the inch worm, repeat the full movement until the destination is reached.

blogPosts.title: Earl Fonda
blogPosts.description: You perform the exercise on a 4 count. First count is the upward motion of the jane fonda, second count is the downward motion, but you suspend your leg without touching the ground. The third count is bringing your leg up towards your chest and fourth count is extending the leg. Your leg will not touch the ground until the desired amount of reps are completed.

blogPosts.title: Imperial Blocker
blogPosts.description: Imperial Walker using a cindy/coupon. The pax starts with the cindy overhead. As the pax brings a knee up to their stomach, he lowers the cindy to the down position of an overhead press with a slight twist toward the knee brought to his stomach. Cindy is returned overhead as his leg returns to the ground. Alternate legs performed in four count cadence.

blogPosts.title: Upper Decker
blogPosts.description: Best used with sturdy picnic table or stairs. PAX will step up to the tabletop (two steps) when on top perform one air squat and step down.

blogPosts.title: Cocaine Bear Crawl
blogPosts.description: Bear crawl across a parking lot, stopping at each white line to perform a merkin, bringing your nose to the white line.

blogPosts.title: Zombie Walk
blogPosts.description: A lunge walk over a long distance that causes the PAX to groan and stumble like the Walking Dead.

blogPosts.title: Zombie Crunch
blogPosts.description: LBC with both legs bent/laid to one side (like a dead zombie). Then repeat for other side.

blogPosts.title: Zombie Crawl
blogPosts.description: Start in a plank position and crawl with both legs dragging behind. For an added challenge, try a Zombie Crawl on an incline.

blogPosts.title: Zig-Zag Hops
blogPosts.description: Find a beam, log, or other object to jump over. Start on one side and hop over in a zig-zag fashion from one end to the other.

blogPosts.title: Zebra Butt-Kicks
blogPosts.description: The zebra kick is all about the gluteus maximus. From plank, bend your knee to 90 degrees and kick skyward. High reps, imagine your heel busting up the chops of a lioness.

blogPosts.title: Yves Poll
blogPosts.description: Yves Poll (pronounced "eves pole" in English) is a term for running backwards or backpedaling. He was a French marathon runner who ran backwards all the time.

blogPosts.title: Yurpee
blogPosts.description: Burpee variation in honor of the Ruskie (Yuri Verkhoshansky), who developed plyometrics to train Olympians: The merkin at the bottom of the burpee is a clap-merkin, and on the up portion, there are two tuck jumps per burpee. Basically, its a Clurpee with two tuck jumps.

blogPosts.title: Yul Brynner
blogPosts.description: Yul Brynner was an actor in the 1960s movie The Magnificent Seven. The Magnificent Seven Merkins involve progressing through seven different types of merkins without stopping or holding plank between each one: Carolina Dry Dock, Wide Merkin, Normal Merkin, Ranger Merkin, Diamond Merkin, Crucible Merkin, and Chuck Norris Merkin. Rinse and repeat on the Q's call.

blogPosts.title: Yoke Walk
blogPosts.description: Many different variations with this one, but you'll need something heavy to carry across your shoulders and behind your neck. Can involve a heavy bar for a single pax member or pax can team up with heavy objects like logs.

blogPosts.title: X-Cross Sit-up
blogPosts.description: Lie on your back with your legs and arms extended in an 'X' position. On count 1, simultaneously lift your left leg and right arm to meet above your core, keeping both as straight as possible while touching your right hand to your left leg. Return to the starting 'X' position. On count 2, switch to lifting your right leg and left arm, again keeping both as straight as possible while touching your left hand to your right leg above your core. Return to the starting 'X' position. On count 3, execute a knee-up by lifting your shoulders and legs off the ground and touching your toes as you bring your knees up, with only your lower back in contact with the ground. On count 4, extend your arms and legs and return to the starting 'X' position.

blogPosts.title: Worst Worst Merkin Ever
blogPosts.description: Thats right, it can ALWAYS be worse! Done in cadence: start with a Crucible Merkin on 1, a Wercan on 2, a regular Merkin on 3, and a Diamond Merkin on 4. Do ten of these, and you'll agree its the worst of the worst.

blogPosts.title: When Animals Attack
blogPosts.description: Mark off an area (kill zone). All PAX must remain in the area at all times. One PAX (the attacker or "it") starts in one corner, while all the other PAX start in the opposite corner. Assume the bear crawl position and stay there. The attacker begins to chase the other PAX throughout the kill zone (in bear crawl mode). Once contact is made with a PAX ("tag"), the contacted PAX becomes the new attacker, returns to their corner, and the game starts over. Adjust the exercise based on the size of the kill zone and the number of people.

blogPosts.title: Wheel of Merkin
blogPosts.description: Grab a piece of curb and start in an incline plank position. Perform a set number of reps in each merkin position before rotating to the next. Begin with an incline merkin. Then, rotate 90 degrees clockwise until your body is parallel to the curb, with your left hand and foot on the curb and your right hand and foot off it. Perform a merkin, then rotate another 90 degrees and perform a decline merkin. Rotate 90 degrees again and repeat, this time with your right hand and foot on the curb and your left hand and foot off it.

blogPosts.title: We're Not Worthy
blogPosts.description: With arms extended outward, lower and raise your arms.

blogPosts.title: Walmart Burpee
blogPosts.description: The burpees discount-store cousin, where the fun is dialed back. Start by dropping into a squat like a normal burpee, but continue all the way down to your back, rolling onto your shoulder blades. Roll forward, and when your feet hit the ground, place your hands in front and jump back into a plank. The rest follows a standard burpee: perform a merkin, a thruster, and then jump with your hands overhead.

blogPosts.title: V-Up Roll Up
blogPosts.description: Performed in a 4-count cadence, this exercise is best known from P90X's Ab Ripper. Start by lying flat with your arms extended above your head. Perform a full sit-up and touch your toes. As you return to the starting position, when your mid-back touches the ground, begin to raise your legs to a 45-degree angle and hold them there. Then, crunch up and touch your toes while keeping your legs in position.

blogPosts.title: Tony Hawk Burpee
blogPosts.description: A normal burpee but when you jump, do a 360 degree spin in the air each time.

blogPosts.title: Reverse Indian Run aka Indian Giver
blogPosts.description: Reverse Indian Run aka Indian Giver
blogPosts.imageAltText: Reverse Indian Run aka Indian Giver

blogPosts.title: Prisoner Cell Merkin Burpees aka PCMBs.
blogPosts.description: Prisoner Cell Merkin Burpees aka PCMBs.
blogPosts.imageAltText: Prisoner Cell Merkin Burpees aka PCMBs.
